n Middlebury VT."},"INST024":{"id":"INST024","primary_name":"Litchfield Law School","name":"Litchfield Law School","short_name":"Litchfield Law School","alt_names":[],"type":"law_school","founding_year":1784,"location":{"city":"Litchfield","state":"Connecticut"},"wikipedia_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Litchfield_Law_School","primary_persons":["X00614","H00912","H00913"],"hooker_connected_people":["HD2045","H00840","HD1347","HD2047","H00912","TD0239","I00900","H00797","H00913","H00826","HD2619","H01141"],"person_ids":["X00503","X00614","X01916","X02832"],"national_historic_landmark":true,"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":[],"sources":[],"notes":"Founded 1784 by Judge Tapping Reeve (X00614) — the first law school in the United States. Tapping Reeve married Sarah \"Sally\" Burr Reeve (H00912), 5th-generation Hooker descendant, daughter of Esther Edwards Burr (H00378). Aaron Burr Jr. (H00913) — 5th-generation Hooker descendant — studied law here under his brother-in-law Tapping Reeve before enlisting in 1775. Among Litchfield's other notable students: John C. Calhoun (also became VP — two Vice Presidents produced by one law school). The school ran until 1833; at its peak enrolled students from across the country. Tapping Reeve House and Law School designated National Historic Landmark, 1965. In 1781, Reeve (with Theodore Sedgwick) represented Elizabeth Freeman (\"Bett\") in Brom & Bett v. Ashley — case that led to abolition of slavery in Massachusetts. Reeve also brought Rev. Lyman Beecher (father of Harriet Beecher Stowe) to Litchfield. The Litchfield Law School is among the most consequential institutions connected to the Hooker tree.\n[hooker_connection] founded by in-law of Hooker descendant; Hooker descendant studied here"},"INST022":{"id":"INST022","primary_name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","name":"American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions","alt_names":["ABCFM","American Board"],"type":"missionary_